######################################################################################################################
we are including some top 30 git commands needed for our Day to day activities and out of 10 which we use rarely!!#####
######################################################################################################################
######################################################################################################################
git init: Initializes an empty Git repository in the current directory.
git clone: Copies a remote Git repository to your local machine.
git add: Adds changes in the working directory to the staging area.
git commit: Commits changes from the staging area to the local repository.
git status: Shows the current status of the repository.
git diff: Shows the difference between the working directory and the staging area.
git log: Displays the commit history of the local repository.
git branch: Lists all local branches in the repository.
git checkout: Switches between branches or commits.
git merge: Merges changes from one branch to another.
git remote: Shows a list of remote repositories.
git fetch: Downloads changes from a remote repository to the local repository.
git pull: Downloads and merges changes from a remote repository to the local repository.
git push: Uploads changes from the local repository to a remote repository.
git tag: Creates or lists tags in the repository.
git reset: Resets the repository to a previous commit or to the state before changes were staged.
git revert: Creates a new commit that undoes changes from a previous commit.
git stash: Temporarily saves changes that are not ready to be committed.
git cherry-pick: Applies a specific commit to the current branch.
git show: Displays information about a specific commit.
git config: Configures Git settings.
git rm: Removes files from the working directory and the repository.
git mv: Moves or renames files in the working directory and the repository.
git grep: Searches for a specific string in the repository.
git blame: Shows who made changes to a specific line of code and when.
git submodule: Manages submodules in a Git repository.
git archive: Creates a tar or zip archive of the repository.
git bisect: Helps find the commit that introduced a bug.
git log --graph: Shows the commit history as a graph.
git reflog: Shows a log of all Git actions, including those that were undone.
